                2295
            ],
            "ignore": false,
            "order": 18,
            "anno_id": 1,
            "text": "## **3.3 History-aware Response Generator**",
            "line_with_spans": [
                {
                    "category_type": "text_span",
                    "poly": [
                        1270.0000000000002,
                        2245,
                        2080,
                        2245,
                        2080,
                        2295,
                        1270.0000000000002,
                        2295
                    ],
                    "text": ""
                }
            ],
            "attribute": {
                "text_language": "",
                "text_background": "",
                "text_rotate": ""
            }
        },
        {
            "category_type": "plain_text",
            "poly": [
                1275.0000000000002,
                2322.5,
                2192.5,
                2322.5,
                2192.5,
                2995,
                1275.0000000000002,
                2995
            ],
            "ignore": false,
            "order": 19,
            "anno_id": 1,
            "text": "Inspired by CopyNet (Gu et al., 2016), we construct two vocabularies, *i.e.*, generic vocabulary  $V_g$  and history-aware vocabulary  $V_h$ , to better generate history-aware responses. The generic vocabulary  $V_g$  contains the words that appear in all the training dataset, and the history-aware vocabulary  $V_h$  only contain the words that appear in the history conversations  $H$ . To generate a word of the response, the response generator will choose to generate a generic word from  $V_g$  or directly copy a word from  $V_h$  based on the switching mechanism (Gulcehre et al., 2016).",
            "line_with_spans": [
                {
                    "category_type": "text_span",
                    "poly": [
                        1275.0000000000002,
                        2322.5,
                        2192.5,
                        2322.5,
                        2192.5,
                        2995,
                        1275.0000000000002,
                        2995
                    ],
                    "text": ""
                }
            ],
            "attribute": {
                "text_language": "",
                "text_background": "",
                "text_rotate": ""
            }
        },
        {
            "category_type": "plain_text",
            "poly": [
                1280,
                2995,
                2195,
                2995,
                2195,
                3232.5,
                1280,
                3232.5
            ],
            "ignore": false,
            "order": 20,
            "anno_id": 1,
            "text": "Specifically, at each decoding time step  $t$ , we feed  $C_s$ ,  $S_c$  and the ground truth word sequence before  $t$  into  $n_{dec}$  Transformer decoder layers and obtain a hidden representation vector  $o_t \\in \\mathbb{R}^d$ . The",
            "line_with_spans": [
                {
                    "category_type": "text_span",
                    "poly": [
                        1280,
                        2995,
                        2195,
                        2995,
                        2195,
                        3232.5,
                        1280,
                        3232.5
                    ],
                    "text": ""
                }
            ],
            "attribute": {
                "text_language": "",
                "text_background": "",
                "text_rotate": ""
            }
        },
        {
            "category_type": "plain_text",
            "poly": [
                1270,
                1522.5,
                2202.5,
                1522.5,
                2202.5,
                2190,
                1270,
                2190
            ],
            "ignore": false,
            "order": 17,
            "anno_id": 1,
            "text": "By employing attention in the transformer encoder layers, our model can understand the conversation context by attending to all context token embeddings and history conversation memories. We denote this history-aware context encoding by  $S_c \\in \\mathbb{R}^{n \\times d}$ . After context encoding, history conversation memories are updated based on the latest information from the current conversation context. We denote this context-updated history memory as  $C_s \\in \\mathbb{R}^{M \\times d}$ . The concatenation of  $C_s$  and  $S_c$  over the first dimension will become the input of the response generator.",
            "line_with_spans": [
                {
                    "category_type": "text_span",
                    "poly": [
                        1270,
                        1522.5,
                        2202.5,
                        1522.5,
                        2202.5,
                        2190,
                        1270,
                        2190
                    ],
                    "text": ""
                }
            ],
            "attribute": {
                "text_language": "",
                "text_background": "",
                "text_rotate": ""
            }
        },
        {
            "category_type": "plain_text",
            "poly": [
                1265,
                1177.5,
                2200,
                1177.5,
                2200,
                1512.5,
                1265,
                1512.5
            ],
            "ignore": false,
            "order": 16,
            "anno_id": 1,
            "text": "layer  $E_m$  to obtain a sequence of context token embeddings  $\\mathbf{S} = {\\mathbf{s}^1, \\mathbf{s}^2, \\cdots, \\mathbf{s}^{n_x}}$ , where  $n_x$  is the length of the context sequence. Next, we concatenate the history memory matrix  $\\mathbf{C} \\in \\mathbb{R}^{M \\times d}$  with  $\\mathbf{S} \\in \\mathbb{R}^{n_x \\times d}$  over the first dimension and apply  $n_{enc}$  Transformer encoder layers.",
